<br>
Her slim fingers cradled a tiny glass vial, filled with a liquid that resembled quicksilver. Over and over she turned it in her hands, watching the potion flow round and round as her heart steadily pounded in her breast. The day had just begun; all was still silent around her, as silent as her voice had been for all of her nineteen years. But those few precious drops of quicksilver in her trembling fingers could change all that. <br>
<br>
Months ago she’d happened upon a bit of text in her studies, alluding to a ceremony once performed to cure a young girl not unlike herself. In truth, she’d never dreamed of such a thing being possible. In her exuberance, she’d carried the volume to her guildmates, to the clerics Kaidric and Landric. She remembered how she shifted foot to foot as the two of them read, her vibrant slate gray eyes watching both of them for their reactions. The two had brightened though worry creased their brows. The potion called for was nearly impossible to create, dangerous in the least and possibly deadly to consume. Kaidric had taken the book, and promised her he’d consult with more people, and that was the last she’d heard about it for weeks. <br>
<br>
Truthfully, she’d nearly forgotten about his promises. The mute girl had spent much time in the Defender’s Hall and had not seen Kaidric. Then, a few days ago he’d found her, and gently pushed into her palm the small glass vial. Quietly he whispered to her of the dangers, that it might even kill her if she tried it. He asked her to let him be there for her, and silently she’d nodded. <br>
<br>
But as the last few days went by, as she debated in her heart and mind if she should attempt this cure, she knew she had to do it alone. She’d risen this morning well before dawn, and made her way to the one spot that held any meaning for her. A small patch of soft, sweet grass along the riverbank was where she headed. Even now, the flush crept across her cheeks as she recalled the night spent here in his arms, the first night she’d spent with any man. His soft, trembling voice as he told her he’d loved her and promised his life to her for always. Carrington, the word tumbled silently through her mind. He’d disappeared from her after she’d lost their child, after the tiny life was snatched away from them. Where he’d gone, she knew not. Whispers and rumors she’d caught over the months, snatches of conversations. But none of that mattered, the spot was still special to her and here of all places, she felt returned to those days where someone found her beautiful and special even in her silence. <br>
<br>
All around her, the hills of Camelot still lay sleeping as she worked free the tiny cork. Her tongue rolled in her mouth, wetting her lips as she swallowed hard against her fears. A silent prayer and she upended the vial against her lips. The foul taste nearly gagged her as it slithered across her tongue and the quicksilver potion disappeared down her throat. Savagely it burned the tender flesh and she coughed and sputtered. A wave of dizziness careened through her and she doubled over, arms clasping her stomach and her eyes clenched shut. <br>
<br>
Her stomach roiled about, threatening to spew its contents and she fought it. The precious potion was irreplaceable, and she kept it down with the force of her will. Sweat slicked her skin as she struggled, and then the visions began to swim across her closed eyelids. The touch of a kindly cleric carrying a new babe in the crook of his arms; the same cleric laying in a pool of his own blood as an assassin carried her away. A woman frozen in the snow and the gentle eyes of a highlander scout as he brought away his Sarrah, and her mind swam with the remembering of her life with him. Trucking through the frontiers with the tall scout, and the small amber flower that once graced her slender neck she recalled vividly, as well as the moment of his death at the hands of a kobold shadowblade. <br>
<br>
She groaned and rolled to her side, wrapping herself into a tight ball of pain. Other images kept flowing through her mind, the kindly friar that had taught her to read and write. There stood Carrington clutching a small child to his chest, gazing at her hopelessly as her heart broke. The Norseman Kelryck who’d taken away the pain of her loss and brought her back from the brink of self-destruction. She could almost feel the touch of his beard and hear the soft laughter spill from his lips. More rapidly the images flew by, almost her entire life became one huge blur of colors as she lay there gasping for air. <br>
<br>
Blackness crept into the edges of her vision, and began to cover the flashing images of her life. Slowly it edged across, as her heart slowed and her body slowly relaxed. There on the edge of the river, as the world began to awaken around her, a young friar gave into the void that sought to claim her. She fell back into the icy waters of darkness, and her heart stopped beating. <br>
