<br>
Kaidric sat in the study of his brother Rynnthorn’s estate. The room was fairly ornate; the desk and book shelves were trimmed with gold, the chairs covered with skins of rare beasts. Kaidric sat in one such chair, reading what an old volume of some sort. <br>
<br>
The book itself was unremarkable, much like the man reading it. He was tall for a Briton, but rather plain looking. Still wearing his unadorned, dull silver armor; made for him by his brother’s friend Athelston. His chain helm lay resting on the desk alongside the book and the cloak of his wood was pulled back. <br>
<br>
Kaidric’s blue were so fixated on the passage he was reading that he did not hear his brother Rynnthorn enter the study. Rynnthorn and Kaidric were very dissimilar. Rynnthorn was a politician who occasionally passed for a soldier of Albion. Kaidric had no interest in politics, and was instead fully devoted to the Church of Albion and her teachings. They had little in common, beyond the blood of their shared father, but still they had found brotherhood after years of separation. <br>
<br>
Rynnthorn stood over Kaidric for a full few minutes before giving up on getting his attention. “Kaidric.” Rynnthorn spoke, rather loudly. <br>
<br>
Kaidric barely moved, his eyes did not leave the page. He simply raised his hand in the air, holding up a chain clad index finger to indicate he needed a moment. <br>
<br>
Rynnthorn sat down in a chair, noticeably irritated at having to wait. He shifted around in his chair impatiently, hoping the noise would distract his brother. <br>
<br>
“Rynnthorn?” Kaidric looked up at his brother. <br>
<br>
“Kaid, what are you doing here?” Rynnthorn asked, he wasn’t used to either of his brothers stopping by often. Predian was always off defending the frontiers and Kaidric preferred the surroundings of the church. <br>
<br>
“This book, the one you found about restoring Rhalm’s voice. There was a passage I wanted to re-read.” Kaidric paused before continuing. “It’s bothering me Rynnthorn. It talks about giving something up, in order to regain one’s true voice. I need to learn more before she takes the potion.” <br>
<br>
“Kaidric, you should find her then.” Rynnthorn withdrew a bell from inside his pocket and rang it. A few seconds later a well dressed servant entered the hall. Rynnthorn turned his attention to the servant. “Where was the friar, Rhalm, last seen?” <br>
<br>
Kaidric rose to object, unaware and visibly bothered that his friend was being followed. Before he could voice an objection, the servant described the river bank where Rhalm was. <br>
<br>
“Rynn!” Kaidric scowled. <br>
<br>
“Relax brother, my people keep tabs on our entire family and their friends, in case of an…emergency.” <br>
<br>
Kaidric was visibly angered but his desire to find his friar friend was overwhelming. He scopped up the book under his arm, returned the chain helm to his head and pulled his cloak’s hood forward. <br>
<br>
Kaidric stormed out of the room and then the estate, without another word to Rynnthorn. At the estate’s stables, he mounted a horse and road off to the river bank. He ran his horse along the river bank, looking for Rhalm. What he discovered instead, shook his soul. <br>
<br>
The girl lay still with an empty vial next to her. Rhalm had taken the potion. <br>
<br>
Kaidric dismounted from his horse and approached Rhalm. Her body seemed lifeless and a sense of urgency overcame the cleric. He instantly summoned the Church’s powers of healing and cast a spell on the girl. No effect. <br>
<br>
Angrily and with more desperation, he called upon the Church again, to raise the dead. The spell failed. He tried to cure her of poisons and then of diseases with no result. Now teering, the cleric repeated every spell known to him, shouting angrily at the God to which he prayed. <br>
<br>
Rhalm’s body remained lifeless, and Kaidric fell to his knees over her, sobbing. He reached into his pouches, searching for something to use out of desperation. He withdrew a small leather bag filled with strange leaves and herbs. A healing mixture his Druidic sister had given him. <br>
<br>
He fought to remember what his sister had said about the herbs, he could hear Thrennoadae’s voice, but not make out what she was saying. With his mace, he ground the herbs as finely as he could, scooped them up into his hands and forced them into Rhalm’s mouth. He forced her unmoving body to swallow them. <br>
<br>
His heart broken, angry at the Church for not giving him the power to heal, sad for the loss of his friend, and full of guilt for providing the potion; the cleric collapsed over Rhalm’s body.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#A0B0E0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thrennoadae>Thrennoadae</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#3333ff>(6/16/03 8:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenterfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=149.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A Voice Never Heard</span><hr size=1> She drifted on a sea of blackness, inky soft velvet darkness that seeped through her limbs with its cold fingers and pulled her through the currents of her mind. Voices from her past whispered to her as she floated near, idle remnants of her life like flotsam in her wake. A pinprick of light illuminated the darkness and silently she began to move towards it. The depths of her memories around her grew warmer, more comforting as the light grew brighter. <br>
<br>
Slate gray eyes began to blink away the sheer magnitude of its dazzling light as she drew close enough to lift upwards an arm, finger extended as she sought to merge herself into that beautiful white light. From the darkness around her she felt the embrace of the souls that had passed before her, the love from each caress of her past. She heard her name whispered from each mouth, each name different yet still her own. She felt the bittersweet kisses pressed to her forehead as she came ever closer to that sweet white glow. <br>
<br>
“Mother?” she murmured as her eyes fell upon the figure of a woman. Golden hair flowed about her, illuminated by the grace of the light behind her. A gentle smile formed on her lips and she opened her arms wide to Rhalm. <br>
<br>
“MOTHER!” she exclaimed and fought the murky sea that tried to hold her back. Slogging through the darkness she reached out and her arms wrapped about the figure of the woman. Shuddering tears shook her body as her arms wrapped about the slender woman, and her mother held her tight. A tingling coursed through her veins like fire, yet there was only comfort in that sweet embrace. <br>
<br>
“Rhalm, you must listen to me,” came her mother’s voice. <br>
<br>
“No mamma, don’t send me away,” she whispered back. <br>
<br>
“Rhalm, it’s not time for you yet, Rhalm, you must go back.” <br>
<br>
Tears flowed from her eyes and she looked past her mother’s shoulder and there stood the scout, the only man she truly loved as her father. She almost laughed to see his fiery red hair again, that kind smile on his face. <br>
<br>
“Father,” she squealed, at once resembling the five year old girl she had been last she’d seen him alive. <br>
<br>
“Sarrah, me sweet Sarrah,” and his arms wrapped about her and she was whisked through the air. “Sarrah, ye must listen ta me..” <br>
<br>
“No poppa, don’t send me away,” she replied. <br>
<br>
“Sarrah, its nae time fer ye yet, Sarrah, ye must go back.” <br>
<br>
Both figures dimmed and it was then she heard the sound of sobbing from somewhere in the darkness. She tilted her head to the side, and it sounded a bit louder. She turned her eyes again to the prismatic light that tugged at her and she took a step forward. Her mother and father’s eyes pleaded with her. <br>
<br>
“Rhalm, not yet...” <br>
<br>
“Sarrah, nae yet...” <br>
<br>
Behind her, she could hear the sobbing again, and her eyes swiveled to her mother. “Mother, what.. what is happening?” <br>
<br>
The woman’s silvered fingers reached up and stroked against Rhalm’s cheeks, and her gentle blue eyes filled with love and sadness. “You must go back Rhalm, its not your time. But, there is a price.. You will have your voice, but you must leave something else behind.” <br>
<br>
The words confused her as the sobbing behind her grew louder. She felt compelled backwards through the inky darkness, to the coldness. “Momma… I don’t understand… Help me?” Her face turned from the light as she began to push backwards, the light fading behind her. “Momma?” her voice called plaintively again. <br>
<br>
No reply was heard. <br>
<br>
She drifted back through the memories of her life, and uncomprehendingly watched as each one dimmed, and sank out of sight. She glanced back towards the light, and the figures of her parents were gone from view, as was the warmth of their arms about her. All about her, it grew darker and darker, the black emptiness chilling her through, while the sobbing grew louder. <br>
<br>
In a rush, she felt herself slammed against a cold, hard wall, and then her eyes blinked away the touch of daylight. She felt a solid weight against her and groaned as she tried to shove it away. Kaidric rubbed at his eyes in disbelief as he felt Rhalm move against him, heard the sudden rush of breath as she inhaled. Her grayish skin slowly grew warm again, filling with the vibrancy of life. <br>
<br>
He watched as her eyes opened, those stunning slate gray eyes as they blinked away the light of the sun. <br>
<br>
“Rhalm.. Rhalm.. are you alright?” <br>
<br>
Her face swiveled to his voice, eyes slowly focusing on his face. Her mouth moved as if she was attempting to speak, but no sound passed her lips. Kaidric sighed, it failed, the potion failed, he thought to himself. He brushed her hair from her face, and offered a weak smile to comfort her. She wet her lips, and tried to speak again, this time, a soft sound whispering from her mouth. <br>
<br>
He blinked and leaned close, trying to understand. She tried again, and this time, he could hear her words. <br>
<br>
“Who are you?” she whispered. <br>
