<br>
The girl’s eyes fluttered as she tried to focus on his face, and in a voice hardly more than a whisper she uttered, “Who?” <br>
<br>
Gently, laughing more from relief than anything, he lowered his voice and said, “You can speak! The potion worked. Rhalm.. it’s amazing!” <br>
<br>
Her eyes narrowed and she shook her head. “What .. do you mean?” It voice was soft, tentative as she forced the air from her lips. <br>
<br>
“Your voice, it’s returned. You can speak.” Worry began to inch its way back into Kaidric’s heart as he gazed at his friend. She didn’t seem to recognize him at all. Those beautiful eyes that once shared his laughter seemed empty of recognition. The soft voice coming from her lips gave him hope though, yet the responsibility for her condition fell across his shoulders. <br>
<br>
Slowly she sat up, pushing herself back a few inches with a groan, and gazed warily at the cleric. Again she repeated, “Who are you?” <br>
<br>
“Kaidric. You know me Rhalm,” came his reply. The fear clamped in his stomach. What had he done? Slowly he slipped off his hood and his helm, hoping the sight of his face would jog her out of whatever it was. <br>
<br>
A bit of a breeze drifted across the pair, stirring the cloak across his back, and a few stray locks of her dark hair twirled across her cheek. Gently she bit down on her bottom lip, then whispered, “I do not know you. Rhalm, … is that my name?” <br>
<br>
“Yes, Rhalm is your name, you don’t remember? <br>
<br>
“I remember.. other names.” <br>
<br>
“What names?” <br>
<br>
She searched her mind, seeking those thoughts that twisted and evaded her grasp. They darted about as if afraid of the light touch of her mind, eluding her. “Evee … Sarrah. I am Sarrah.” She clung to that name as it surfaced and refused to let it free. She was Sarrah. Bits of other stray thoughts associated with that name came clear. <br>
<br>
“No, you are Rhalm, you have always been Rhalm.” Kaidric picked up the tiny vial, shaking his head sadly. “You drank this, to bring back your voice…” he trailed off, unable to admit his fault in helping her. <br>
<br>
“I do not understand,” a slight scowl touched her features as she shook her head and gazed at the vial in his fingers. <br>
<br>
“I thought you had died…” and anguish cut him off as he felt again that emotion when he’d caught sight of her limp form strewn across the ground. “Your breath was gone, and I could not heal you. What is the last thing you remember?” <br>
<br>
Long moments passed as she gazed across the river. She could hear the sounds of his chain clinking lightly as his weight shifted, the soft inhale and exhale of his breath. Her palms pressed against the leather that confined her as she turned over and over that one memory she’d been able to clasp. “An amber necklace.. of a flower.. and a bearded man.” <br>
<br>
“I don’t know those things. Rhalm, I don’t know what has happened. <br>
<br>
“Sarrah,” she corrected, clinging to that thought as if it would save her. It touched her gently, to hear the name Sarrah, a soft burr to the voice in her mind. The beard she imagined was not unlike Kaidric’s with its soft glint of red. But the figure shrouded behind the beard and the voice dwarfed Kaidric in size. Gently she repeated, “Sarrah, my name is Sarrah.” <br>
<br>
He fought back the sob that threatened to make him lose what little control he had left. A tear formed in his eye as he acknowledged her, “Sarrah.. What have I done?” She seemed lost in her thoughts, eyes drifting across the water unseeing as she tried to find herself, to remember anything. Gently, his voice pulled her back. <br>
<br>
“Rhal… Sarrah?” <br>
<br>
“Yes?” <br>
<br>
“Do you recognize your possessions? Your leather armor? The papers you carry?” <br>
<br>
Her eyes drifted down to the things around her. A small bag that would hook over a shoulder. A simple wooden staff. Inside the bag she pulled free a sheaf of papers, covered in handwriting. Vaguely, she heard him speaking to her still, yet she was distracted by the written words. <br>
<br>
He pulled free a note she’d given him long ago, words inconsequential. “Those are your words.” Her slate gray eyes drifted across it, taking in the words, but no hint of recognition was visible. <br>
<br>
“You say, I wrote that?” Her voice was sounding hoarser, strained, not surprisingly since she’d never used it before. Her eyes strain to find some meaning, some hint of who she was from the words on the paper. Her oval face turns upwards, slate gray eyes filled with uncertainty. “I do not understand. Help me? Help me Kaidric?” <br>
<br>
Gently he grasped her hand, and helped her to unsteady feet. Yet he could feel the shyness in her, and gently released her fingers after he was sure she wouldn’t tumble over. Quietly, he led her to the small town of Cotswold, to the building they kept as a guild house. His heart broke over and over as she passed by person after person, no hint of acknowledgment upon her features. She gazed around as if a newcomer, a stranger. He led her up to the room she claimed as her own, and stepped aside at the doorway. Fingertips ached to reach up and push the stray lock of hair from her cheek, yet he refrained. She had no memory of the kiss they once shared so many months ago. <br>
<br>
“Its late.. this is your room. Tomorrow, we can find the answers Rha.. Sarrah. I will not rest until you are whole again.” <br>
<br>
Those stunning gray eyes gazed at him, clouded over with non-understanding. She nodded, refraining from speaking, her voice gone too hoarse and her throat throbbing with dryness. Quietly, she opened the door and stepped into the darkened room. The sun had just set outside, and the twilight filled the corners, masking from view the furnishings. She took a hesitant step forward, trying to pierce the darkness and Kaidric sighed, and gently pushed past here. <br>
<br>
“Here.. the candle is here,” he quietly said, then lit it. “We would talk sometimes, at night after dinner.” The flame was lit with his flint, but the light was not bright enough to illuminate the blush on his cheeks. She glanced about, though the room was rather well-kept and there were not many articles on display. <br>
<br>
”Thank you,” she forced out, wincing. <br>
<br>
“Tomorrow then? I promise you, we’ll fix this ..Sarrah. I promise.” <br>
<br>
Quietly he exited the room, pulling the door shut behind him. Inside, she sat down in the darkness, illuminated with the flicker of one single candle. She fingered the bedspread as she stared at the belongings of a stranger. “Sarrah,” she whispered through cracked lips. “I am Sarrah,” and she clung firm to that one memory, lashing her entire being to it tightly and refusing to let it sink into oblivion. <br>
<br>
The full touch of darkness seeped into the realm of Albion, and carried to bed its inhabitants. One lone building, one lone room, one lone girl awash on the tides of a mishap of birth, floundering through the morass of a price she unwittingly paid. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#A0B0E0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thrennoadae>Thrennoadae</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#3333ff>(6/18/03 5:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenterfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=149.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A Voice Never Heard</span><hr size=1> A few days had gone by, and true to his word Kaidric tried everything in his ability to help Rhalm. Nothing worked. His angst grew as did his frustration, gazing upon the sweet face of the girl he’d only wanted to help, the tears welled up in his eyes. Inwardly he vowed again that he’d make right this horrible wrong, but he was at his wits end. Perhaps Landric would know, but Landric had moved on and he knew not where to find him.<br>
<br>
In the meanwhile, Rhalm, or Sarrah as she thought of herself, was trying to adjust to her life. The room she stayed in pleased her well enough, there was a small window with a beautiful view of the city of Camelot. At night the torches that lit the gates flickered just out of direct view, and the seat at the window let her watch the people passing in and out of the capital. She’d taken to watching people, listening to their voices as they spoke. Voices in anger, happiness, greeting, voices lifted up in happy song as some of the rover bands would arrive. A few made her laugh out loud, once she was brought to tears as she watched the sad parting of a couple. <br>
<br>
As for her own life, she didn’t really live at all in those first days. Her sleep was a tormented waste of time as she tumbled across the sheets, flitterings of her past brushing butterfly wings across her sub-conscious. The voices came to her still, teasing her with hints of recognition then laughing mockingly as they darted away, tearing free the gossamer strands of her memory as she tried to clutch them to her.<br>
<br>
Only the one memory was hers to keep. She was Sarrah. The bearded man, the amber necklace she was still trying to decipher, but she *knew* she was Sarrah.<br>
<br>
It was mid afternoon and she’d taken a horse ride to Avalon, and the shimmering purple-blue of the portal to Gothwaite Harbor beckoned her. She stepped through and her senses were immediately assaulted by the smells and sounds of the harbor. The fresh ocean air with its hint of fish, the sand beneath her feet making walking a bit more challenging. Proud adventurer’s setting forth with weapons readied as they rode deep into the heart of the Avalon Isle. Something inside her whispered that she too had done such a thing. But the staff she carried felt awkward in her hands. The mace slung at her hip offered no comfort either. She’d objected when Kaidric had asked her to continue to wear what she’d always worn. But the look in his green eyes had changed her mind. He was trying to help, even though she didn’t fully understand.<br>
<br>
So she still dressed in her leathers, though she had no intentions of fighting anything. She still carried her staff, but it was merely a walking stick. She wandered around the town, admiring a few of the shops when she’d found a group of people working with cloth. A few strands of silk caught the wind, and the ends tumbled recklessly as they caught a stray beam of light. Rhalm stepped closer and watched for a while, listening to the women talk softly and laugh amongst themselves as their fingers wove through the fabric, and needles darted. <br>
<br>
After many long minutes, one woman about her own age, noticed Rhalm and beckoned her over. “You look as if you want to try,” and she smiled up at her. Rhalm shrugged her shoulders and laid her staff down beside her as she knelt. “Here, like this…” and the girl handed her a square of leather, a needle and some linen thread. Carefully she began to sew, making sure to lean over and gently correct Rhalm as she watched and learned.<br>
<br>
“My name is Emilli,” she said, then introduced the rest of the circle. <br>
<br>
“Sarrah, my name is Sarrah.”<br>
