<br>
The sweet, mute girl had changed. She’d always had her own mind, her own desires, but so easily did everyone around her transform that nod of yes, into whatever it was they wished her to say. For her, it had been easier to simply agree and go along with their whims than to try to push against the flow. How did a mute argue with someone unwilling to read her words?<br>
<br>
She might not remember her past, but now she did not forget her voice. And use it she did. One morning, Kaidric was at her door again, bright and early with another visit to yet another elder cleric planned. Rhalm padded to the door, clasping a robe around her small body as she gazed up to see Kaidric’s face. She scowled. <br>
<br>
“No Kaidric. Not today,” and she started to push the door shut. <br>
<br>
“What do you mean? I’m trying to help you Rhalm.”<br>
<br>
“My name is Sarrah,” she repeated, for the hundredth time. “And I am fine, I don’t need your help!”<br>
<br>
“But Rha.. Sarrah, you have no memories, you…” her glare cut him off. Those slate gray eyes of her flashed with anger he’d never seen before. He was hurt deeply, knowing he’d brought this on her. “Its my fault, I’m trying to fix it. Please?”<br>
<br>
Her ire was up, and she never been able to express it like this before. Perhaps she didn’t realize that, but part of her could feel it. And it felt damn good. “GO AWAY!!” she yelled, waking up half the guild hall in the process. “I don’t WANT your help. GO AWAY and leave me BE!!” she bellowed at him, the anger coursing through her.<br>
<br>
The hurt look upon his face as he nodded and turned away finally broke through the anger she felt. Her body was tense and overwrought, her emotions were raw, but that pained look he gave her was as if a bucket of ice had been dumped on her head. She eased the door shut, ignoring the looks from the other guild mates as they peeked their heads into the hall. As the door clicked closed, she leaned her back against it and her body slid to the floor in a heap. She felt the tears rising and the tightening at the back of her throat. Drawing her knees to her chest, she buried her face against them as she tried to drown the sound of her own sobbing. <br>
<br>
Down the hall, Kaidric heard, but his humiliation overrode his feelings, and he forced his feet to continue their path. If she didn’t want his help, he’d not force it on her. But it wouldn’t stop him from seeking the answers himself.<br>
<br>
***<br>
<br>
Hours later, after she’d dried the tears and made her way once again to Gothwaite, she was yet again working with her needle and thread. A stray lock of hair obscured her vision a moment, and she sunk the needed into her finger with a soft yelp of pain. She stuck the offended digit into her mouth, tasting the tang of the blood and a jolt hit her. Her vision swam and she saw a small house, a hovel against a river bank. She felt the sting of a slap against her cheek, the bite as her teeth closed on the flesh of her mouth. In her mind’s eye she saw the woman as her hand drew back again, and felt the ringing in her ears as her hand connected with Rhalm’s face again.<br>
<br>
“Lazy wench! Little lazy tramp!!” echoed in her ears and she dropped the stitching in her lap. Her fingertips pressed tight to her temples as she tried to push away the memory. “Better fer all if the likes o’ ye were just dead and gone!” came the voice again, and Rhalm felt herself crawling away and curling into a ball to hide the pain she felt from the beating the woman bestowed upon her.<br>
<br>
Another memory had surfaced, and Rhalm wished it never had. Cold and dark, full of anger and hatred for a girl that had done nothing wrong. A woman taking out her bitterness at life against a mute girl that was hardly more than a child herself, this memory brought nothing but pain and hopelessness back into Rhalm’s life. <br>
<br>
“No,” she thought, she didn’t want to remember that. But try as she might, it would not fade. It bobbed and glinted against the surface of her mind as bright as the sweet memories of the scout with his bearded face, and the lilting voice that called her Sarrah. A mental shove at the memory, trying to dislodge it back to wherever it came from. “I don’t want to be that girl anymore, its not me!” she pleaded with her subconscious, but it still floated there, defiant of her wishes.<br>
<br>
Around her, no one seemed to notice the inner battle she fought, as she quietly picked back up the sewing. Soon her fingers were working the materials again, mindful of the sore fingertip as she glared inwardly at the memory that had surfaced. For now she recalled another name, and it was Rhalm. Rhalm, uttered by a hateful woman instead of the sweet Sarrah of her father’s voice.<br>
